{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2530"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2530"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.13,0.12,0.38,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2530"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2530"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"1380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4845"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11522"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43177"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 76-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with her daughter, who has recently become concerned about her mother\u0027s ability to cope at home. She reveals that over the last two months, her mother\u0027s memory has been \u0022poor\u0022, often forgetting to shower in the morning or pay her bills on time. On further history, little more information is obtained from the patient herself, as she is withdrawn and quiet. She is unable to recall what she had for breakfast and cannot state the day of the week or month. She is unable to recount any childhood memories, however she is able to talk about the early years of her marriage to her late husband, who died six months ago. Her medical history is notable for hypertension, high cholesterol, osteoporosis, and urinary stress incontinence. Her medications include captopril, simvastatin, and denosumab.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 152/94 mmHg, pulse 80/min, and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her facial expression is depressed-looking and poorly responsive, and her movements are slow but not hesitant. Reflexes are all normal, with an absence of primitive reflexes. The mini-mental state examination reveals a score of 18/30, with the patient frequently becoming frustrated and teary during the test. She has a slight tremor of her right hand that only becomes apparent when she writes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Frontotemporal dementia","Vascular dementia","Parkinson\u0027s disease","Depression","Alzheimer\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Edepression.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a two-month history of memory impairment and increased difficulty in completing her activities of daily living. This has occurred in the context of her husband\u0027s death six months ago. Her memory loss is patchy, with impairment of both short-term memory (e.g. unable to remember breakfast) and variable impairment of long-term memory (e.g. unable to recall childhood memories, yet able to remember early years of marriage). On examination, she demonstrates features of psychomotor retardation, including reduced facial reactivity and slowness of gait. Her mini-mental state examination is 18/30, indicating moderate cognitive impairment, and she seems frustrated and upset by her impaired performance. All of these features are highly suggestive of depression (presenting as pseudodementia) being the most likely cause of her presentation. Depression is a diagnosis, whereas pseudodementia is a label applied to one specific clinical presentation of that diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontotemporal dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a likely diagnosis in this case. Patients with frontotemporal dementia will generally present with a number of features suggestive of frontal lobe impairment, including social disinhibition, incontinence, and hyperorality. Primitive reflexes may be present. This patient has none of these symptoms (although she does have a pre-existing history of stress incontinence). Classically, patients with frontotemporal dementia will be younger than those with Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, dementia with Lewy bodies, and vascular dementia. They also tend to have relatively higher mini-mental state examination scores. A mini-mental state examination score of 18/30 is not consistent with this diagnosis. For these reasons, frontotemporal dementia is not the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient exhibits risk factors for \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E, with advanced age, hypertension, and high cholesterol all contributing to an increased risk. Having said that, vascular dementia tends to progress over a period of years in a \u0022step-wise\u0022 fashion, with patients experiencing sudden and noticeable cognitive insults with each cerebrovascular event. Signs of upper motor neuron injury are also often present on physical examination. The cognitive impairment in this patient appears to have developed more quickly than one would expect in vascular dementia and there is no evidence of an upper motor neuron lesion on physical exam. Therefore, vascular dementia is not a correct answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is very unlikely in this case, as the dementia associated with this progressive neurological illness develops years after it is first diagnosed. There is no history of Parkinson\u0027s disease in this patient and whilst she does have a tremor on physical examination, this is not the resting \u0022pill-rolling\u0022 tremor usually seen in Parkinson\u0027s. It sounds more like an essential tremor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common single cause of dementia (combined Alzheimer\u0027s and vascular dementia is more common overall). It typically develops over a period of years and results in insidious cognitive decline. Patients will generally experience impairment in short-term episodic memory (e.g. forgetting appointments, forgetting tasks), with sparing of earlier memories. This patient\u0027s rapid cognitive decline and pattern of memory impairment is inconsistent with a diagnosis of Alzheimer\u0027s disease, as is the frustration and distress noticed during mini-mental state examination testing. Patients with Alzheimer\u0027s will often have limited insight into their poor mini-mental state examination scores compared with patients who have depression. For these reasons, Alzheimer\u0027s disease is an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Depression can often present under the guise of pseudodementia."],"references":["Arvanitakis Z, Shah RC, Bennett DA. Diagnosis and management of dementia: review. JAMA\u202f: the journal of the American Medical Association. 2019 Oct;322(16):1589\u201399","Mukku SSR, Dahale AB, Muniswamy NR, Muliyala KP, Sivakumar PT, Varghese M. Geriatric Depression and Cognitive Impairment-An Update. Indian J Psychol Med. 2021;43(4):286-293. doi:10.1177/0253717620981556"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2530"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-29T21:51:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T11:43:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2530"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49495"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}